In a recent interview, President Trump shared his thoughts on his spiritual experience during his COVID-19 diagnosis and expressed gratitude for the prayers he received from Americans. He acknowledged the influence of Evangelical leaders in his life and their love for the country and God. While he grew up attending a Presbyterian church, he now considers himself a non-denominational Christian. President Trump highlighted his efforts to support persecuted Christians worldwide, such as bringing Pastor Andrew Brunson home from Turkey and advocating for religious freedom at the United Nations. He also mentioned the establishment of the White House Faith and Opportunity Initiative, which aims to involve the faith community in government and address various issues such as poverty, mental health, and crime.